Deep dive into computer vision¶

Using CNNs for transfer learning

This notebook illustrates how to classify satellite images for disaster detection. Since we do not have a lot of data available of disaster images we use transfer learning to learn initial features of satellite images and then extend it to support disaster images.

The explanation for this notebook has been inspired from [https://towardsdatascience.com/transfer-learning-using-differential-learning-rates-638455797f00]

So what is transfer learning?¶

It is the process of using the knowledge learned in one process/activity and applying it to a different task. Let us take a small example, a player who is good at chess can apply that knowledge in learning how to play checkers.

How to do it?¶

We take a pretrained network and and train only the newly added layers. This works well when the tasks are related to each other and you have a small amount of data.

The following steps describe how to load the dataset and a pretrained model. The dataset we are using is from the kaggle competition [https://www.kaggle.com/c/planet-understanding-the-amazon-from-space/data]

You may notice that the data available from this kaggle competition are general satellite images. So how does this connect to disaster images?

Trust me, there's a connection

"differential learning rates"¶

Once we have a decent classifier trained we want to use something called "differential learning rates" to not just train our last layer in the network but all of them.

Differential learning rates mean that we use different learning rates for different parts of the network during our training. The idea is to divide the layers into various layer groups and set different learning rate for each group so that we get ideal results.

Why is this helpful?¶

In general, higher layers learn generic features like edges, shapes and the middle layers learn specific details to the dataset

So we don't want to change the initial layers too much but middle layers will have knowledge of the complex features that might help our task.

Testing¶

After we've finished training we can look out test results. One of the cool things we do during testing is that we apply "test time augmentation." What this does is basically changes the image size, angle, shape etc and tries to fool the network into thinking its a different image.

How is this useful? Remember we said we are short on data. If we use a lot of images for training we'll have even less for testing. Using "test time augmentation" we can use a slightly modified different version of the same image. Its also useful because it lets us test whether a slightly modified image can give us the same result hence, confirming the robustness of the network.

def plot_img(fnames,frame, figsize=(16,8), rows=1, data_path=DATA_PATH):
    f = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for name in range(len(fnames)):
        img = PIL.Image.open(data_path+fnames[name]+'.jpg')
        tag = frame.loc[frame['image_name'] == fnames[name]]['tags'].iloc[0]
        sp = f.add_subplot(rows, len(fnames)//rows, name+1)
        sp.set_title(tag, fontsize=10)
        sp.axis('Off')
        #print(tag)
        plt.imshow(img)

New Network¶

Similar to before we initialize a pretrained network. But this time we start from the network we just trained. The idea is that now that we have a network that understands features of satellite images in general, we can use it to pick up features of floods as well.
